sec.p:
Eriophyoid mites are among the smallest arthropods in the world, along with members of other acarine groups such as dolichocybids, acarophenacids (Heterostigmata) and tydeids (one of the putative closest relatives to eriophyoids), as well as insect groups such as feather-winged beetles ( Ptiliidae ) and chalcidoid wasps ( Trichogrammatidae and Mymaridae ) (Grebennikov 2008 ;
Polilov & Beutel 2010 ;
Walter et al.2009 ). The miniature size of eriophyoids, combined with the presence of complexes of morphologically similar species and the deficiency of reliable diagnostic characters represents a major impediment for alpha-taxonomy and systematic research on eriophyoid mites. The search for new characters and methods of analysis for improving the systematics of Eriophyoidea is one of the major goals of modern eriophyoidology. This can only be achieved through detailed comparative morphological studies across different species and higher taxa.

Although the ornamentation and finer structures of the external cuticle of eriophyoid mites may be best studied under scanning electron microscopy (SEM; Craemer 2010 ), CLSM may produce results more quickly than with SEM because of the simpler method of specimen preparation. Results can enhance those obtained from standard optical (phase or differential interference contrast) microscopy (
Chetverikov 2012 b
). For example, details of the prodorsal shield ornamentation and shape of the opisthosomal microtubercles are much sharper under CLSM (compare
&
). Other external elements may also appear to be remarkably clearer under CLSM , such as the eye-like structures of O . sibirica
sp. nov. ,
which were relatively poorly defined under phase contrast (compare
&
B). The easier detection and interpretation of structures with CLSM is essentially due to the main characteristic of this technology: only in-focus information is collected and blurred images are blocked (
Klaus & Schawaroch 2006 ), this way, eliminating the noise from out-of-focus light which is more or less retained under standard light microscopy. In brief, when many specimens are available, and with moderate effort and precautions (e.g. a limited number of images can be captured due to rapid photo-bleaching, which depletes autofluorescence and renders specimens obsolete for CLSM ;
Chetverikov 2012 b
), confocal microscopy imaging may go a long way in enhancing species descriptions and generating new taxonomic information.

When fresh material is not available for study, but there are microscope slides of mites made in appropriate medium (for example Hoyer’s medium), one can produce a three-dimensional reconstruction of the surface of the mite’s body and explore its topography and variability (for example
&
). Hence, 3 D modelling based on stacks of CLSM images can be considered as an alternative or additional method to SEM.

For a group that is as diverse, economically important and character-poor as the Eriophyoidea , molecular methods as well as CLSM and 3 D modelling techniques have been surprisingly little used for species delineations and even less so for improving systematics per se (
Navajas & Navia 2010 ;
Chetverikov 2012 b
). The COI sequence data produced for Oziella sibirica sp. nov. (available in GenBank under accession number NCBI JQ 342669 ) may help to distinguish related species in the future and perhaps also clarify relationships with close genera (e.g.
Navajas et al.1996 ). However, more slowly evolving markers should also be studied, across phytoptid taxa, since molecular data overall is very badly needed as a supporting tool for eriophyoid systematics. Since many phytoptid taxa inhabit exotic plants that sometimes only have a narrow distribution in remote regions of the world, a revision of the Phytoptidae would have to be conducted through international collaboration. This is even more vital because most modern techniques and associated facilities are not yet widely accessible. Resolving the phylogeny of phytoptid taxa and their relatives ( Phytoptidae is probably not monophyletic) and in turn establishing a classification that reflects natural groupings will help to open the door to evolutionary hypotheses about host plant associations and other life history traits as biological knowledge advances in parallel.
